===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|in||lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*in}} (whence German {{term|in|lang=de}}, Dutch {{term|in|lang=nl}}, Danish {{term|i|lang=da}}), ultimately from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*en}}, whence also ultimately Latin {{term|in|lang=la}}, Irish {{term|i|lang=ga}}, Welsh {{term|yn|lang=cy}}, Ancient Greek {{term|·ºêŒΩ|tr=en|lang=grc}} (modern Greek {{term|ŒµŒΩ|lang=el}}), Old Armenian {{term|’´||tr=i|lang=xcl}}, Old Church Slavonic ''v≈≠(n)-'', Russian {{term|–≤|lang=ru}}, Old Prussian {{term|en|lang=prg}}, Lithuanian {{term|ƒØ|lang=lt}}.

====Preposition====
{{en-prep}}

# [[contain|Contained]] by.
#: ''The dog is '''in''' the kennel.''
# [[surround|Surrounded]] by.
#: ''We are '''in''' the enemy camp.''
#: ''Her plane is '''in''' the air.''
# [[part|Part]] of; a [[member]] of.
#: ''One '''in''' a million.''
# Pertaining to (that particular thing).
#: ''He has passed '''in''' English.''
# Immediately [[after]] a period of [[time]].
#: ''They said they would call us '''in''' a week.''
# [[within|Within]] a certain time constraint
#: ''Are you able to finish this '''in''' three hours?''
#: ''The massacre resulted in over 1000 deaths '''in''' three hours.''
# By virtue of; by means of
#: '''''In''' replacing the faucet washers, he felt he was making his contribution to the environment.''
#* '''1898''', {{w|J. Meade Falkner}}, {{w|Moonfleet}} Chapter 4
#*: '''In''' returning to the vault, I had no very sure purpose in mind; only a vague surmise that this finding of Blackbeard's coffin would somehow lead to the finding of his treasure.
# {{non-gloss definition|Indicating an order or arrangement.}}
#: ''My fat rolls around '''in''' folds.''
# [[into|Into]].
#: ''Less water gets '''in''' your boots this way.''
#* {{quote-news
